with movement of the voltage sensor from the resting to the activated state, and in BK channels it is very rapid compared with the opening of the pore and rise of Kϩ current (Fig. 3a). Thus the movement of the voltage sensor is essentially complete before channels open, and IgON reflects voltage sensor movement when channels are closed. The amplitude of IgON is slightly larger in 10 mM than in 0 [Mg2ϩ]i (Ϸ10% increase at ϩ250 mV; data not shown), whereas the time course of IgON is not altered (Fig. 3c). The relationship between gating charge movement and membrane voltage when channels are closed (QC-V relation), determined by integrating the area under the IgON traces at various voltages, exhibits no significant change between 0 and 10 mM [Mg2ϩ]i (Fig. 3b) (Ϸ10-mV difference in the voltage at the half-maximum of the QC-V relation, Vhc). These results indicate that Mg2ϩ does not affect the closed channel significantly, which may also explain why Kϩ ionic current (IK) activation kinetics are insensitive to Mg2ϩ (Fig. 2d).
On the other hand, off Igs (IgOFF), which reflect the return of the voltage sensor from the activated to the resting state, are decreased in amplitude and slowed by 10 mM [Mg2ϩ]i (Fig. 3 c and d). Under our experimental conditions (see Methods) Kϩ currents through the

