pore are blocked but channels are still open in response to depolarization (31). Therefore, a fraction of channels are open at the end of a voltage pulse when IgOFF is recorded. To examine whether the change of IgOFF is related to the fraction of open channels, we measured IgOFF after pulses of various duration (Fig. 3c). After a 0.30-ms voltage pulse, few channels are open and IgOFF is similar in the presence or absence of Mg2ϩ. However, as pulse duration increases IgOFF amplitude is greatly reduced in 10 mM [Mg2ϩ]i (red traces, Fig. 3c), indicating that Mg2ϩ affects voltage sensor movement more significantly when channels are open. Previous studies indicate that voltage-sensor deactivation is slowed when channels are open even in the absence of Mg2ϩ (31, 32) (Fig. 3d). In our experiment at ϩ250 mV, channels should be almost maximally activated in the presence or absence of Mg2ϩ (Figs. 1d and 3b).

